Fire weather synoptic patterns 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Synoptic patterns help us understand how the climate system drives meteorologica
l events.
 Fire weather in southeastern Australia has a typical pattern.
 Over the Tasman Sea, a quasi-stationary anticyclone is present.
 Its circulation advects hot and dry air from the interior of the continent.
 These environmental conditions make vegetation prone to fire ignitions.
 At the same time, a cyclone over the Southern Ocean supports the arrival
 of cold fronts to this region.
 These cold fronts can turn a “bad” fire weather day into a catastrophic
 event.
 They change and extending the flank of the fire fronts (citations).
 Several fire weather studies describe this pattern (citations).
 Most investigations focus on the catastrophic events (citations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mills (2005) performed an evaluation of the meteorological conditions of
 "Ash Wednesday".
 Mills (2005) proposed a parameter to assess and predict fire weather.
 The study used the 850 hPa level horizontal temperature gradient.
 The cyclone-anticyclone dipole structure is the basis for this parameter.
 Extreme fires are more likely to occur when there are greater temperature
 differences between the cold front air mass and the hot column of air over
 southern Australia.
 Using this criterion, Mills (2005) established that "Ash Wednesday" ranks
 in the 0.1% of events using 40 years of reanalysis data.
 On the other hand, reproducing the arrival of cold fronts is the key factor
 in forecasting extreme fire weather (citations).
 Mills (2005) investigation also comprised a simulation that provided further
 insights on the wind structures that made “Ash Wednesday” catastrophic.
 It highlighted that not only the mobility of the frontal system created
 this extreme fire event, but also the depth of the trough system.
 In this study, the cold front arrival was simulated with a 1-hour lag.
 Over time, computer simulations of extreme fire events in this region have
 become more sophisticated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Engels et al.
 (2012) simulated the meteorological conditions of "Black Saturday".
 Their study focused on simulating with great detail the mesoscale phenomena.
 It reproduced the arrival of the cold front of that day with a 30 minutes
 lag compared to observations.
 The investigation also determined the spatial and temporal variability
 of fire danger.
 Using the results of the numerical model, the McArthur's Forest Fire Danger
 Index was computed (Noble et al., 1980).
 The paper demonstrates how changes in temperature, humidity and wind influenced
 the spatial and temporal variability of fire danger on "Black Saturday".
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mills (2005) and Engels et al.
 (2012) are examples of a typical approach to examine fire weather in this
 region.
 Several studies focus on a single case study to simulate and explain fire
 weather behavior (citations).
 “Ash Wednesday” and "Black Saturday" are the most relevant cases regarding
 human fatalities and economic impact (citations), and therefore the focus
 of great research attention.
 Investigating single case fire weather studies has been useful to identify
 the main characteristics of these events.
 However, fire weather research with a long-term synoptic approach has been
 less common.
 Exploring the synoptic climate signal based on a long-term analysis could
 contribute to extending the lead time of the forecasts.
 Addtionally, a synoptic climatology could contribute to better understand
 the mechanisms that drive fire weather.
\end_layout

