\begin_layout Standard
Boschat et al.
 (2014) examined the large-scale connections between heatwaves in Victoria
 and extreme rainfall events in Queensland.
 The co-occurrence of these events motivated this study.
 However, this study found that there is no dynamic link between heatwaves
 extreme rainfall events in Victoria and Queensland respectively.
 Tropical convection drives extreme rainfall events in Queensland.
 This convention usually occurs during strong “La Nina” events.
 On the other hand, heatwaves in Victoria are locally driven.
 An anticyclone produced by a wave train amplification that starts in the
 in the Indian Ocean generates heatwaves.
 Boschat et al.
 (2014) acknowledge that this anticyclone pattern is also present during
 extreme rainfall events in southern Queensland.
 However, the air parcel tracking allowed to determine that a different
 process forms this anticyclone.
 The high pressure system forms as part of a tropical-ex-tropical influence
 of "La Nina" events.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pezza et al.
 (2012) and Boschat et al.
 (2014) investigations undertake the synoptic climatology approach that
 seems less explored in fire weather.
 It appears that a lack of robust fire activity records hampers these studies.
 For example, Mills (2005) and Reeder et al.
 (2015) rely first on weather parameters to identify extreme fire days.
 Mills (2005) used the 850 hPa horizontal temperature gradient before the
 cold front arrival.
 On the other hand, Reeder et al.
 (2015) used the temperature difference after the passage of the cold front.
 In both cases, they validated they approaches with the available fire activity
 dates.
 These dates are scarce in the scientific literature.
 Therefore, the logical behind their approaches is sound.
 Oficial bushfire records of the Victorian Government have not been peer-reviewe
d.
 However, they have been used in other fire investigations (Harris 2013).
 Therefore, they could be useful to investigate long-term fire weather patterns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximum and minimum temperature are the basic variables to compute heatwaves.
 Long-term and high-quality records of these variables span the entire the
 entire 20th century.
 For example, the Australian Climate Observations Reference Network - Surface
 Air Temperature (ACORN-SAT) dataset (citation).
 Therefore, the feasibility to perform long-term analysis increases.
 Despite this, the long-term analysis of heatwaves only starts on the nineteen-s
eventies.
 For example, Pezza et al.
 (2012) acknowledge that their study period is not long enough to establish
 significant trends.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additionally, the investigations have focused on the sub-regional processes
 that drive fire weather.
 However, climate modes of variability exert a significant influence on
 weather—and fire weather—in Australia.
 For example, “El Nino” events generally bring dry conditions to Australia
 (Risbey, 2009).
 On the other, hand wet conditions are usually linked to a “La Nina” events.
 Moreover, the Indian Ocean dynamics has contributed to several droughts
 in southeastern Australia (citations).
 In fact, positive phases of the Indian Ocean Dipole produce hot and dry
 conditions during in spring in Victoria.
 These environmental conditions contribute to the availability of fuels
 and an increase in extreme fire events in this region (Cai, 2009).
 A large-scale analysis of the weather patterns associated with fire activity
 in this region could offer further insights to disentangle the influences
 of these climate modes of variability over fire weather.
 To accomplish this, a long-term analysis of fire weather is again necessary.
 A synoptic climatology of fire weather could contribute to having greater
 confidence in the global patterns that drive fire weather in this region.
\end_layout

